<BR>Xtal Matrix / Magician of the 30th Nudge-Nudge Wink-Wink
<BR><b><i>-Quezzy-</i></b> / Half-Elven Ranger of the 19th Season 
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/umatches475.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Matches475</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mage</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#333333>(2/26/01 8:03:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerlibrarysubmissions.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=30.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Magician Partner question?!?!</span><hr size=1> My vote would be to get your friend to play a Necro.  I was in a group as a wee little mage with a necro, and the two of us could make the other four members pout because of our dmg output.  We have since started grouping together most of the time, and we have a blast.  Only problem is that we don't do a lot of things which aren't in outdoor zones.  Fear kiting is a bad thing in small spaces   hehehe<br>
<br>
The two of us have very little downtime (except when we switch zones) and we chain pull.  What more can you ask for???  hehehe  If he doesn't want to play the necro, then there are many other good choices.  Shaman's have great buffs for your pet, but the enchanter's buffs/clarity are also a great great thing.  Clerics get some great buffs for your pet too.  <br>
<br>
All and all, make sure what he picks is fun for him.  Anything that he picks has good points for grouping with you.  Have fun with the game, but I still say Necro <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :evil --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/devil.gif ALT=":evil"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ucrispinskyhawk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Crispinskyhawk</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://fp.geocities.com/whisperskyhawke/bluehawk.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#333333>(2/26/01 8:22:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerlibrarysubmissions.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=30.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://fp.geocities.com/whisperskyhawke/bluehawk.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Fear</span><hr size=1> Whenever this question comes up, everyone always mentions Necros, Cleric, Enchanters (because they can fear), and druids (who dot and snare and kite), but if you know what you are doing Monks and Rogues work just as nice.<br>
<br>
There are a couple of ways you can use a Monk or Rogue as your partner.  The first is with a water or air pet.  Let the monster beat on your pet while your partner does instill doubt.<br>
<br>
The second way is to use a earth pet.  Obivously instill doubt doesn't work with this pet but I have found it more effective than fear kiting.<br>
<br>
The key is to the earth pet is placement.  The monster has to be right next to the pet.  Mobs will aggro on the closest thing to them while they are being rooted.  Root itself is a huge taunting spell.  Make sure you malise the monster (for root spell and weapon procs/posion) and damage shield your pet.  If it is done right, all you have to do is sit down and let the Monk/Rogue and your pet beat the snot of of the monster.  The monster either will never turn around or only for the briefest second.<br>
<br>
One more thing, this works best on mobs with a normal to low Magic Resist.  Velious I have noticed has more mobs with higher MR than Kunark or the old world. <p><p><font color="#0000FF">Crispinskyhawke<br>
